            <section class="prose">
              <h2>How the pediatric dosage calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                Pediatric drug doses are often prescribed on a
                <strong>mg per kg</strong> (mg/kg) basis. This calculator helps
                you turn that mg/kg value into a total mg dose and, if you know
                the product strength, into an approximate volume in mL.
              </p>

              <div class="formula-box text-sm">
                <p class="font-semibold mb-1">Core formulas</p>
                <p>
                  <strong>1. Weight conversion</strong> (if weight is given in
                  pounds):
                </p>
                <p>Weight (kg) = Weight (lb) ÷ 2.20462</p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>2. Total dose per dose (mg)</strong> from mg/kg:
                </p>
                <p>Total dose (mg) = Weight (kg) × Dose (mg/kg)</p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>3. Volume per dose (mL)</strong> from liquid strength:
                </p>
                <p>Concentration (mg/mL) = Strength (mg) ÷ Volume (mL)</p>
                <p>
                  Volume per dose (mL) = Total dose (mg) ÷ Concentration (mg/mL)
                </p>
                <p class="mt-2">
                  <strong>4. Total daily dose</strong> (if frequency is known):
                </p>
                <p>
                  Total daily dose (mg/day) = Total dose (mg) × Doses per day
                </p>
              </div>

              <h3>Example: weight-based pediatric dose</h3>
              <p>Suppose you have:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Child's weight: <strong>18 kg</strong></li>
                <li>Prescribed dose: <strong>10 mg/kg per dose</strong></li>
                <li>Liquid strength: <strong>100 mg/5 mL</strong></li>
                <li>Frequency: <strong>3 times per day</strong></li>
              </ul>
              <ol>
                <li>
                  Total dose per dose = 18 kg × 10 mg/kg =
                  <strong>180 mg</strong>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Concentration = 100 mg ÷ 5 mL = <strong>20 mg/mL</strong>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Volume per dose = 180 mg ÷ 20 mg/mL = <strong>9 mL</strong>
                </li>
                <li>
                  Total daily dose = 180 mg × 3 = <strong>540 mg/day</strong>
                </li>
              </ol>
              <p>
                The calculator performs these steps automatically and shows both
                mg and mL values, plus daily totals if you enter the frequency.
              </p>

              <h2>Clinical safety and limitations</h2>
              <p>
                This tool is intended for
                <strong>educational and double-checking purposes</strong>. It
                does not contain internal drug dosing tables and does not tell
                you what dose to use. You must always:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Obtain the correct dose (mg/kg or total mg) from a trusted
                  pediatric reference or prescriber.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Check for <strong>maximum single dose</strong> and
                  <strong>maximum daily dose</strong> limits.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Consider age, organ function, comorbidities, and concomitant
                  medications.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Use extra caution in
                  <strong>neonates and premature infants</strong>, where dosing
                  is highly specialized.
                </li>
              </ul>
              <p class="text-sm text-red-600">
                Never use an online calculator as the sole basis for prescribing
                or administering medication.
              </p>

              <h2>Step-by-step: calculating pediatric doses by weight</h2>
              <h3>1. Confirm the drug and indication</h3>
              <p>
                Different indications for the same drug can have different
                recommended mg/kg ranges and maximum doses. Always verify the
                correct regimen in a current pediatric drug reference or
                institutional guideline.
              </p>

              <h3>2. Obtain an accurate weight</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>Use a calibrated scale whenever possible.</li>
                <li>
                  Prefer weight in kilograms; if you only have pounds, the
                  calculator converts to kg.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Avoid estimating weight by age alone when accuracy matters.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>3. Apply the mg/kg formula</h3>
              <p>Once you know the recommended mg/kg dose:</p>
              <ul>
                <li>Multiply the child’s weight in kg by the mg/kg value.</li>
                <li>
                  Round the result appropriately based on the drug and
                  formulation.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>4. Convert mg to mL using the product strength</h3>
              <p>
                For oral liquids, the label usually states something like
                <strong>125 mg/5 mL</strong> or <strong>250 mg/5 mL</strong>.
                Enter these values to estimate the volume per dose.
              </p>

              <h3>5. Check maximum doses and adjust</h3>
              <p>
                Many pediatric drugs have a maximum single dose and a maximum
                daily dose. If your calculated dose exceeds these limits, you
                must adjust downward according to the reference.
              </p>

              <h2>Frequently asked questions</h2>
              <h3>Can parents use this calculator at home?</h3>
              <p>
                Parents should <strong>not</strong> use this tool to
                independently determine doses without direct guidance from a
                pediatrician or pharmacist. However, it can help parents
                understand how weight-based dosing works and double-check that
                the dose they were given is in a reasonable range.
              </p>

              <h3>Why doesn’t the calculator list specific drugs and doses?</h3>
              <p>
                Drug dosing is complex and changes over time as new evidence
                emerges. Including static dosing tables could become outdated or
                be misapplied. This tool focuses on the
                <strong>math</strong> (mg/kg → mg → mL) and leaves the choice of
                dose to up-to-date clinical references and professionals.
              </p>

              <h3>What about body surface area (BSA)-based dosing?</h3>
              <p>
                Some pediatric regimens, especially in oncology, use mg/m²
                dosing. This calculator is designed for mg/kg dosing. For
                BSA-based regimens, you should use a dedicated BSA calculator
                and drug-specific protocols.
              </p>

              <h3>How should I round the mL dose?</h3>
              <p>
                Rounding depends on the measuring device (oral syringe vs.
                household spoon) and the drug’s therapeutic index. In general,
                use oral syringes for small children and
                narrow-therapeutic-index drugs, and round to a practical
                increment (for example, 0.1 mL or 0.5 mL) as recommended by your
                institution.
              </p>

              <h2>Disclaimer</h2>
              <p class="text-sm text-gray-700">
                This pediatric dosage calculator is provided “as is” for
                educational purposes only. It does not constitute medical
                advice, diagnosis, or treatment. No guarantee is made regarding
                accuracy, completeness, or suitability for any particular
                patient. Always consult a licensed healthcare professional and
                authoritative references before making any clinical decisions.
              </p>
